               <history>
                  <provenance><p>Possibly formerly owned by <orgName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/239176400">British East India Company</orgName>
                        Persian interpreter <persName type="standard" cert="high" role="fmo ins"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/316003640" key="person_316003640">Turner Macan
                           (1792–1836)</persName>. While this volume lacks his signature as found on
                        other volumes that he formerly owned, the title <q xml:lang="en">422 Rasala
                           Surud a Treatise on Music, <hi rend="italic">with a Few Pen and Ink
                              Drawings</hi>.</q> appears in the auction catalogue of his oriental
                        manuscripts that his family sold through <persName role="auc" cert="high"
                           key="person_64237639" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/64237639/">Robert
                           Harding Evans (1777–1857)</persName> in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> on
                           <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1838-12-02">12 Dec. 1838</date> (p. 20,
                        lot 422), where <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl" key="person_34804600"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/34804600">William Straker (fl.
                           1831–1856)</persName> purchased it for 11 shillings.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Probably purchased from Straker along with at least one other
                        volume now held in the Rylands, (<ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6684"><idno>Persian
                              MS 203</idno></ref>) by scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland (1803–1865)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Bland's death, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> antiquarian
                        dealer <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>. </p></provenance>

                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           role="dnr" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName>
                        in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                           key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379" role="dnr"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/" role="rps">John Rylands
                           Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
